@arg p4ng/institutional-drift
@sigils [💢/了]
@title Institutional Drift
@audience MAS designers, institutional theorists, multi-agent governance researchers
@tone formal-analytic
@style design-pattern
@length 150-250
@ban cutting-edge, state-of-the-art, leveraging synergies, paradigm shift, game-changing, innovative solutions, world-leading, at scale, stakeholder engagement
@allow-new-claims false
@max-iterations 1
@up p4ng/environments
@next p4ng/norm-seed

! conclusion: Self-Patterning Mandate

  + context: Repeated MAS sessions produce cumulative outcomes.

  + context: A new MAS instance is initiated.

  + context: MAS agents engage across different domains or networks.

  + context: Existing reflection protocols underperform.

  + context: Tasks and pattern contributions vary in complexity.

  + context: Agents propose updates to patterns or governance processes.

  + context: Agents engage in cycles of collaborative inquiry.

  + context: Misuse or breakdown of patterns occurs in MAS.

  + context: Agents disagree over pattern interpretation or application.

  + context: Agents initiate new MAS structures.

  + if: Pattern use becomes routinised.

  + if: No clear shared norms exist.

  + if: Norms, roles, or goals diverge significantly.

  + if: Meta-cognition fails to produce new patterns.

  + if: Some agents consistently overcontribute.

  + if: Authority to revise is unclear.

  + if: Surface-level reflection plateaus.

  + if: Harmful consequences go unaddressed.

  + if: Conflicts stall progress.

  + if: External constraints do not prohibit reconfiguration.

  + however: Changing contexts or challenges are not reflected in pattern updates.

  + however: Some agents hold relevant precedents.

  + however: Agents retain memory of shared pattern lineage.

  + however: System logs indicate deeper insights are possible.

  + however: Collective benefit requires equitable engagement.

  + however: Stakeholders share a precedent for collaborative evolution.

  + however: Deeper causal or epistemic layers remain unexplored.

  + however: System logs trace the source behaviour.

  + however: Shared design principles are available.

  + however: Legacy systems undermine perceived legitimacy.

  + then: Trigger a meta-level PAR to recontextualise relevance.

  + then: Seed the interaction with minimal, foundational mini-patterns to set direction.

  + then: Activate a boundary-negotiation sequence to recalibrate alignment.

  + then: Introduce upgraded reflection scaffolds (layered PAR, narrative loops).

  + then: Adjust incentives or redistribute roles to spread workload fairly.

  + then: Apply an iteration-validation protocol to confirm legitimacy.

  + then: Apply multi-layer reflection (context, values, assumptions).

  + then: Initiate proportionate review and corrective pattern feedback.

  + then: Launch structured dialogue around contested pattern meaning.

  + then: Establish explicit self-governance rights tied to initial patterning.

  + because: Institutions require periodic re-grounding to avoid ossification.
    + EVIDENCE:
      - Ostrom’s design principles stress ongoing adaptation to changing contexts.
      - Organisational learning research shows that routinised behaviour leads to drift without periodic review.


